 the company is built around three divisions orthopaedics medsurg medical and surgical devices and neurotechnology and spine stryker is highly diversified and no single product line represented more than  percent of revenues in  stryker’s largest segments were medical instruments medsurg –  percent of revenue knee replacements orthapaedics –  percent endoscopy medsurg –  percent hip replacements orthapaedics –  percent trauma and extremities implants orthapaedics –  percent stryker’s medsurg unit dominates medical instruments sales in the us holding a  percent share of the  billion market the company’s operating room equipment can be found in roughly  american hospitals and includes power tools for surgery fluid and waste extraction and computer and robotassisted surgical devices orthopaedics — hip knee ankle and trauma implants — accounted for  percent of stryker’s sales in  the most of any of the three sectors the company held  percent of the hipreplacement market in the us and  percent of kneeimplant market making it the third largest player in each in may  stryker announced it would begin issuing payments to about  people injured by two models of its hip implants as part of a  billion court settlement the company agreed to in late  starting at  per failed implant the individual payments may be higher depending on the number and types of complications patients suffered stryker from bed builder to diverse medical technology company in  dr homer stryker rented space in kalamazoo michigan’s borgess hospital to set up an orthopedics practice he used a basement room to work on ideas for medical tools one of his first inventions was something he called a “turning frame” it was a hospital bed that allowed doctors to reposition patients as needed while keeping the patient immobilized the bed was popular with doctors and hospitals that started placing orders and stryker hired his first employee to manufacture it in  in  stryker incorporated his business as the orthopedic frame company featuring just four products the turning frame a walking heel for casts a surgical traction device and a cast cutter removing casts remained a difficult and time consuming process in  dr stryker hit on an idea for an oscillating saw using the motor from a malted milk mixer the device could quickly slice through hard casts but its blade did not cut skin it was the beginning of stryker’s move into medical technology devices stryker’s oscillating saw stryker’s oscillating saw to remove hard casts was his beginning move into medical technology devices in  the orthopedic frame company recorded its first year of more than  million in sales the company had  employees and about  percent of its products were the result of dr stryker’s own inventiveness in  the company changed its name to stryker corporation and dr stryker finally retired from his medical practice devoting full attention to being chairman the next  years saw major growth as stryker began expansion into international markets started acquiring other companies and issued an initial public offering ipo on the nasdaq dr stryker died in  the company he started in a basement nearly  years earlier reached  million in sales and established the forerunners to its current divisions that same year in the decades after its founder’s death stryker would focus on international expansion developing new technology and acquiring other companies innovation and acquisitions make stryker a global medical device leader in the s stryker acquired synoptics allowing an entry into endoscopy markets rolled out the first cordless heavyduty power tools for orthopedics and marketed the first liquidproof surgical video camera and the first chip medical video camera providing higher quality resolution than previous surgical cameras in  stryker’s annual sales hit  million in the s the company expanded into canada latin america japan china and hong kong and continued opening new offices in europe in  stryker acquired swiss company osteo allowing stryker to enter the orthopedic trauma market one of the company’s most important turning points came in  when stryker acquired pfizer’s howmedica division for  billion — the largest business transaction in stryker’s history the purchase of pfizer’s howmedica division nearly doubled stryker’s size and sent the company’s annual sales ballooning to  billion a year overnight stryker became one of the biggest players in the global medical technology industry in  stryker made the fortune  for the first time with  billion in annual sales during the early s the company continued expansion to new countries across europe and entry into other fields such as pain intervention surgical navigation and surgical waste management it also created lines of hip and knee replacement implants specifically designed for the japanese market between  and  stryker closed more than  acquisitions of other companies or divisions it spent more than  billion dollars to acquire two more companies in  annual sales topped the  billion mark for the first time when the company posted  billion in sales for  stryker hip implants have been subject to recalls and lawsuits amid all its growth and innovation some of stryker’s products have led to expensive recalls and court settlements in  stryker recalled more than  of its rejuvenate and agb ii modular hip stems after people implanted with the devices developed medical complications some components in the devices were made of a proprietary chromiumcobalt crco alloy one of the symptoms people had were elevated levels of the two metals’ ions in their body stryker modular hip components the problems were connected to stress and corrosion where the implant components came in contact with one another this caused the release of minute amounts of the metals which studies linked to bone and tissue destruction stryker advised people with the devices to consult with their doctors even if they weren’t experiencing symptoms more than  lawsuits over the devices were combined in a multidistrict litigation mdl in a minnesota federal court in  mdls allow similar lawsuits to move more quickly and efficiently through the legal system in  the company agreed to a  billion settlement with plaintiffs individual compensation started with a  base payment with larger amounts for people who suffered additional complications or multiple surgeries in  stryker recalled another crco alloy hip component for a problem called “trunnionosis” this was a condition in which small particles of the metals were released around a component called the trunnion the erosion could damage bone and tissue and could even cause the device to fail when the components became “disassociated” from each other more than  components called lfit anatomic cobaltchromium v femoral heads lfit v were recalled in april  six federal lawsuits over the lfit v were combined in an mdl in a massachusetts federal court at least  other lawsuits filed at the time were expected to potentially join the mdl in may  the new jersey supreme court ordered all state lawsuits there consolidated into a multicounty litigation mcl at least  lawsuits had been filed in new jersey by march  stryker cooperates with federal investigations into company subsidiaries in september  stryker was the only one of america’s five largest orthopedic implant manufacturers who escaped paying into a multimillion settlement with the federal government over allegations of kickbacks to doctors for using their products and costs being passed onto medicare and medicaid zimmer inc depuy orthopaedics inc biomet inc and smith  nephew inc all paid a portion of the  million settlement stryker quickly cooperated with the us department of justice doj investigation led by then us attorney chris christie while the company was not required to pay into the settlement stryker agreed to the same nonprosecution agreement npa as the other firms the npa required all five companies which controlled  percent of the orthopedic implant market at the time to implement reforms and agree to federal monitoring for  months two months later in november  stryker agreed to pay  million to the federal government to settle a doj investigation into a former subsidiary physiotherapy associates stryker had sold the outpatient physicaltherapy business to chicago privateequity firm water street healthcare partners for  million in june  “under the terms of the sale agreement stryker will retain responsibility for certain cash damages to be paid in connection with the previously announced investigation of physiotherapy associates’ billing and coding practices by the united states department of justice” stryker said in a statement at the time “the company will continue to fully cooperate with the department of justice until this matter is ultimately resolved” stryker corporate headquarters the settlement resolved the federal government’s claims that physiotherapy falsely billed medicare medicaid and the defense departments tricare health care programs for services in  stryker subsidiary otismed and its former ceo pleaded guilty in federal court to intentionally distributing kneereplacement related devices that had not been approved by the fda otismed paid more than  million in fines criminal forfeitures and interest to the federal government former ceo charlie chi was sentenced to two years in prison for his role the illegal distribution happened before stryker acquired otismed in november  and stryker cooperated with the doj investigation but under terms of the conviction the otismed subsidiary was banned from participating in medicare medicaid tricare and other federal health programs for  years stryker also agreed with federal prosecutors to comply with doj measures at the new acquisition to prevent future misconduct there robotics d printing featured in stryker’s future stryker’s future remains largely focused on innovation a reflection of its founder’s own inventiveness stryker spent  million on rd in  and has spent  percent or more of its revenue on research and development each year since  its acquisitions have also focused on bringing in new technology developed by others some of stryker’s most forwardlooking innovations involve robotics and d printing in  stryker acquired orthopedic surgery robot maker mako surgical for  billion the devices are designed to make surgery more precise for doctors and less painful for recovering patients the mako system is used for planning kneereplacement surgery prior to the operation and assisting during surgery the system creates a d model of how the knee implant will fit doctors are able to plan the procedure before ever entering the operating room and adjust the fit of the implant to the patient the system also assists the surgeon in precisely removing bone to implant the replacement knee stryker reported installing  of the robots in the third quarter of  alone accounting for what the company called “ percent yearoveryear growth” in mako system sales in  stryker introduced its mako roboticarm assisted total knee system the new robotic system combined mako technology with stryker’s triathlon implant system for total knee replacement since receiving fda approval in  two of the components in the triathlon tritanium knee system have been d printed styker’s new knee replacements stryker is combining robotics and d printing to create and implant knee replacements in  the us food and drug administration fda granted k approval for stryker’s tritanium pl posterior lumbar cage the spinal implant is manufactured with the company’s tritanium ingrowth technology which uses d printing to create implants that mimic the porous nature of bones this allows the implant to function in much the same way as natural bone as bone tissue grows around it stryker has developed a proprietary d printing process called amagine — the “am” stands for “additive manufacturing” the industry’s name for d printing working from a computer model of the part a laser melts and creates layers of titanium powder welding layeruponlayer as it builds the finished component the customized implants can be based on a patient’s individual anatomy and needs in  the company was building a new “center for excellence” in cork ireland that would include a d printing and manufacturing facility in may  stryker’s senior director for platform technology said the company was considering working with hospital chains to develop small d printers that could quickly produce custom implants on site speaking at a convention and trade show for the aerospace defense and medical device industries gene kulesha said the innovation could be less than a decade away he outlined the idea of small d printers each with its own team of “print engineers” the engineers would gather data on a patient’s unique requirements design custom implants and deliver them for surgery within six hours author terry turner terry turner is an emmywinning former television journalist turned senior writer at drugwatch in more than  years of reporting he has seen countless examples of how people armed with comprehensive quality information have the power to make better decisions for their lives and holding those who harm them accountable tturnerdrugwatchcom hide sources stryker  annual review  retrieved from httpwwwstrykercomdocsstrykerarpdf stryker  november fact sheet retrieved from httpwwwstrykercomenuscorporateaboutusnewsroomfactsheetindexhtm stryker nd company history retrieved from httpwwwstrykercomenuscorporateaboutushistoryindexhtm stryker  may  stryker orthopaedics  settlement program reaches milestone retrieved from httpstrykermodularhipsettlementcomdocsstpressreleasepdf stryker  march  company overview retrieved from httpwwwstrykercomstellentgroupscorporatedocumentswebprodpdf plaintiffs’ steering committee mcl   january  settlement slide  retrieved from httprejuvenatehipsettlementcomcategorysettlement fdagov  august  class  device recall stryker lfit anatomic v femor